Figs 
<number id="3DF41346FF959E703DC9FABFFED6FA3C" box="[220,299,1392,1418]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="31.5" valueMax="40.0" valueMin="23.0">23–40</number>
</figureCitation>
): a well defined epicranial stem present behind median dorsal frontoclypeus; anterolateral margins of epicranial suture not clearly defined (visible as slightly darker line after head was cleared and ventral mouthpart complex removed); front margin of head (
<figureCitation id="13071DE4FF959E703E12FA0FFC6DFA6C" box="[775,912,1472,1498]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 24" captionStart-1="FIGURE 25" captionStartId-0="26.[151,255,1755,1779]" captionStartId-1="27.[151,255,1447,1471]" captionTargetBox-0="[560,1041,1257,1708]" captionTargetBox-1="[231,1354,194,1422]" captionTargetId-0="figure@26.[539,1047,1247,1731]" captionTargetId-1="figure@27.[231,1355,194,1423]" captionTargetPageId-0="26" captionTargetPageId-1="27" captionText-0="FIGURE 24. Larva: head, semidiagrammatic, dorsal surface, antennae and mandibles only. M mandible; A 1 - A 3 antennal segments 1 - 3; S stemmata." captionText-1="FIGURE 25. Larva: head anterior half dorsal. Scale bar = 0.43 mm. A, antenna; AM, antennal membrane; S, stemmata; M, mandible." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/181395/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/181396/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Figs 
<number id="3DF41346FF959E703E56FA0FFC6DFA6C" box="[835,912,1472,1498]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="24.5" valueMax="25.0" valueMin="24.0">24–25</number>
</figureCitation>
), with very short rounded median projection (nasale); 
<number id="3DF41346FF959E703C10FA25FEEEF9B2" box="[261,275,1514,1540]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="3.0">3</number>
rd segment of antennae (
<figureCitation id="13071DE4FF959E703F25FA25FD70F9B2" box="[560,653,1514,1540]" captionStart="FIGURE 28" captionStartId="30.[151,255,1624,1648]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1599]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[151,1436,194,1600]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 28. Larva: apical segments of left antenna from below. Scale bar = 150 μm. A 1 - A 3, antennal segments 1 - 3; SC, sense cone antenna." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/181399/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figs 28</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13071DE4FF959E703F8EFA25FD41F9B2" box="[667,700,1514,1540]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="31.[151,255,1478,1502]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,194,1454]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[151,1436,194,1454]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 29. Larva: left antenna detail segment 3 and sense cone. Scale bar = 43 μm. A 3, antennal segment 3; SC, sense cone." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/181400/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">29</figureCitation>
), with elongate slender tip subequal in length to thicker basal portion, and surrounded by 
<number id="3DF41346FF959E703CC9F9DDFE16F99A" box="[476,491,1554,1580]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="2.0">2</number>
strong hairs; sense cone elongate slender. Mouthparts conform to general condition seen in 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C7AE2FF959E703C32F9F4FE17F9E2" box="[295,490,1595,1620]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Pteroptyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="valida">
<emphasis id="B948DD73FF959E703C32F9F4FE17F9E2" box="[295,490,1595,1620]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Pteroptyx valida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except for mandibles, which have 
<number id="3DF41346FF959E703E9DF9F5FC6AF9E2" box="[904,919,1594,1620]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="2.0">2</number>
strong teeth on their inner margin (
<figureCitation id="13071DE4FF959E70382EF9F5FA65F9E2" box="[1339,1432,1594,1620]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="27.[151,255,1447,1471]" captionTargetBox="[231,1354,194,1422]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[231,1355,194,1423]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 25. Larva: head anterior half dorsal. Scale bar = 0.43 mm. A, antenna; AM, antennal membrane; S, stemmata; M, mandible." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/181396/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figs 25</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13071DE4FF959E703D82F9ADFF4AF9CA" box="[151,183,1634,1660]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="29.[151,255,1481,1505]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,194,1457]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[151,1436,194,1457]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 27. Larva: mandibles dorsal. Scale bar = 200 μm. M, mandible." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/181398/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">27</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13071DE4FF959E703DD6F9ADFF19F9CA" box="[195,228,1634,1660]" captionStart="FIGURE 30" captionStartId="32.[151,255,1478,1502]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,194,1454]" captionTargetId="figure@32.[151,1436,194,1454]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURE 30. Larva: ventrolateral view apical half of both mandibles showing inner teeth of left mandible. Scale bar = 136 μm. M mandible." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/181401/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<number id="3DF41346FF959E703DD6F9ADFF19F9CA" box="[195,228,1634,1660]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="30.0">30</number>
</figureCitation>
); labium (
<figureCitation id="13071DE4FF959E703C4FF9ADFE1CF9CA" box="[346,481,1634,1660]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 31" captionStart-1="FIGURE 32" captionStartId-0="33.[151,255,1623,1647]" captionStartId-1="34.[151,255,1485,1509]" captionTargetBox-0="[151,1436,194,1599]" captionTargetBox-1="[151,1434,194,1461]" captionTargetId-0="figure@33.[151,1436,194,1599]" captionTargetId-1="figure@34.[151,1436,194,1461]" captionTargetPageId-0="33" captionTargetPageId-1="34" captionText-0="FIGURE 31. Larva: dorsolateral view, apices maxillary and labial palpi. Scale bar = 120 μm. LA, lacinia; LP, labial palp; MP, maxillary palp." captionText-1="FIGURE 32. as for 31, ventrolateral view, R side only. Scale bar = 120 μm. MP, maxillary palp." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/181402/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/181403/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Figs 
<number id="3DF41346FF959E703C83F9ADFE1CF9CA" box="[406,481,1634,1660]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="31.5" valueMax="32.0" valueMin="31.0">31–32</number>
</figureCitation>
) with an anterior heart shaped prementum and two segmented labial palpi; posterior area consists an elongate mentum which lies between the stipes and extends almost as far as origins of cardines, and a pair of small triangular structures at its posterior end (which may represent the postmentum); apical segment of labial palpi elongate slender pointed, 
<number id="3DF41346FF959E703E35F915FCB1F942" box="[800,844,1754,1780]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4</number>
× as long as width at base; apical segment of maxillary palpi elongate slender acutely rounded, 
<number id="3DF41346FF959E703FAEF8CDFD1DF8AA" box="[699,736,1794,1820]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="2.5">2.5</number>
× as long as width at base (
<figureCitation id="13071DE4FF959E703921F8CDFB6FF8AA" box="[1076,1170,1794,1820]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="27.[151,255,1447,1471]" captionTargetBox="[231,1354,194,1422]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[231,1355,194,1423]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 25. Larva: head anterior half dorsal. Scale bar = 0.43 mm. A, antenna; AM, antennal membrane; S, stemmata; M, mandible." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/181396/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figs 25</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13071DE4FF959E7039B5F8CDFB3DF8AA" box="[1184,1216,1794,1820]" captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="28.[151,255,1448,1472]" captionTargetBox="[231,1355,194,1424]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[231,1356,194,1424]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 26. Larva: head, anterior half, ventral. Scale bar = 0.5 mm. L, lacinia; LP, labial palp; MP, maxillary palp; PM, prementum; POM, postmentum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/181397/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">26</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13071DE4FF959E7039DBF8CDFB13F8AA" box="[1230,1262,1794,1820]" captionStart="FIGURE 31" captionStartId="33.[151,255,1623,1647]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1599]" captionTargetId="figure@33.[151,1436,194,1599]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURE 31. Larva: dorsolateral view, apices maxillary and labial palpi. Scale bar = 120 μm. LA, lacinia; LP, labial palp; MP, maxillary palp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/181402/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">31</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13071DE4FF959E7039E9F8CDFAE0F8AA" box="[1276,1309,1794,1820]" captionStart="FIGURE 32" captionStartId="34.[151,255,1485,1509]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,194,1461]" captionTargetId="figure@34.[151,1436,194,1461]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 32. as for 31, ventrolateral view, R side only. Scale bar = 120 μm. MP, maxillary palp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/181403/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">32</figureCitation>
). Cardines with subtriangular anterior 
<number id="3DF41346FF959E703CC9F8E5FE1AF8F2" box="[476,487,1834,1860]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number id="3DF41346FF959E703CE1F8E5FDF9F8F2" box="[500,516,1834,1860]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="3.0">3</number>
, and elongate slender rod like posterior 
<number id="3DF41346FF959E703EF3F8E5FC08F8F2" box="[998,1013,1834,1860]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="2.0">2</number>
/ 
<number id="3DF41346FF959E703EEAF8E5FBF1F8F2" box="[1023,1036,1834,1860]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="3.0">3</number>
which may incline into head and thus not be clearly seen from below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32652EAFF959E7F3DD3F8B5FAD6FECC" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B830161FF959E7F3DD3F8B5FAD6FECC" blockId="7.[151,1437,152,2020]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1437,152,378]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B948DD73FF959E703DD3F8B5FEC5F822" bold="true" box="[198,312,1914,1940]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Remarks</emphasis>
. This new species brings the number of described 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C7AE2FF959E703E9CF8B4FBEBF822" box="[905,1046,1915,1940]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Pygoluciola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B948DD73FF959E703E9CF8B4FBEBF822" box="[905,1046,1915,1940]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Pygoluciola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species to six. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD7C90FF959E7039DDF8B5FA61F822" author="Ballantyne" box="[1224,1436,1914,1940]" pageId="7" pageNumber="16" refString="Ballantyne, L. A. (2008) Pygoluciola satoi, a new species of the rare SE Asian firefly genus Pygoluciola Wittmer (Coleoptera: Lampyridae: Luciolinae) from the Philippines. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 56 (1), 1 - 9." type="journal article" year="2008">
Ballantyne (
<number id="3DF41346FF959E703843F8B5FA69F822" box="[1366,1428,1914,1940]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="2008.0">2008</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
describes another new species from the 
<collectingCountry id="F32B41F1FF959E703F78F86DFD0CF80A" box="[621,753,1954,1980]" name="Philippines" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Philippines</collectingCountry>
with abdominal modifications conforming to those previously described (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD7C90FF959E703C73F805FD3AF852" author="Ballantyne" box="[358,711,1994,2020]" pageId="7" pageNumber="16" refString="Ballantyne, L. A. &amp; Lambkin, C. (2001) A new firefly, Luciola (Pygoluciola) kinabalua, new species (Coleoptera: Lampyridae), from Malaysia, with observations on a possible copulation clamp. The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 49, 363 - 377." type="journal article" year="2001">Ballantyne &amp; Lambkin 2001</bibRefCitation>
, 2006). The record described here from mainland 
<collectingCountry id="F32B41F1FF959E703822F805FA80F852" box="[1335,1405,1994,2020]" name="China" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">China</collectingCountry>
is exceptional for several reasons: its geographic range, the synchronous flashing, and morphological diversity– it does not possess the elongate projections of male abdominal T 
<number id="3DF41346FF9A9E7F3E99FF0FFC64FF6C" box="[908,921,192,218]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="8.0">8</number>
and 
<date id="FF8227A1FF9A9E7F3EC7FF0FFC0BFF6C" box="[978,1014,192,218]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
V 
<number id="3DF41346FF9A9E7F3EFDFF0FFC0BFF6C" box="[1000,1014,192,218]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="7.0">7</number>
</date>
previously thought characteristic of the genus. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD7C90FF9A9E7F3C01FF27FD7FFEB4" author="Ballantyne" box="[276,642,232,258]" pageId="8" pageNumber="16" refString="Ballantyne, L. A. &amp; Lambkin, C. (2001) A new firefly, Luciola (Pygoluciola) kinabalua, new species (Coleoptera: Lampyridae), from Malaysia, with observations on a possible copulation clamp. The Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 49, 363 - 377." type="journal article" year="2001">Ballantyne and Lambkin (2001</bibRefCitation>
, 2006) included keys to species but this species does not possess the terminal abdomen modifications characteristic of those five species and is not accommodated by that key. In the key to genera here it is the only representative of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C7AE2FF9A9E7F3E04FEF7FC63FEE7" box="[785,926,312,337]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Pygoluciola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B948DD73FF9A9E7F3E04FEF7FC63FEE7" box="[785,926,312,337]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Pygoluciola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
keyed in couplet 
<number id="3DF41346FF9A9E7F3961FEF7FB78FEE4" box="[1140,1157,312,338]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="5.0">5</number>
. Males and females are easily distinguished from existing species by the features listed, especially the dorsal colour pattern.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
